Ask HN: How to get in touch with more clinicians?
text:
Hi HN, I am working on a healthcare startup idea and we are currently trying to validate our assumptions. For this we need to talk to a number of medical professionals within a specific domain. Since my university has access to a university hospital next door we were able to talk to 12 doctors and also the financial administrators to get info about budgets so far. While the feedback was very promising the incubator we applied for wants us to get in touch with at least 100 professionals.

Given that it took more than 1.5 months to get in touch with the previous sample group I was wondering if there was a faster way that I am not seeing. I already thought of faires, but the next relevant fair is a month away and we really need funding asap to keep going.

Ask HN: Anyone Use Zorin OS?
text:
Every couple years I install a new Linux distro on a whim, and I usually go back to Mint or Manjaro (depending on what I'm doing at the time.)

In 2021, I stumbled across Zorin and gave it a try. I figured I'd get rid of it in short order but... I never did. It's just comfy. Things work, it feels nice, hotkeys do what I expect. I feel more comfortable with it than I do with OSX, Windows, or any of the other Unix/Linux distros I use for work.

I never really hear it mentioned by anyone, which sort of makes me wonder how it keeps going. I bought the pro version to support the developers, but didn't end up using any of its features.

Anyone else have hot takes on it?

Ask HN: How do you manage public and private bugs/features/issues?
text:
Currently we use Github for Public Issues(Users reporting issues) and Jira for Private issues(Sprints). But it becomes hard to keep track of both the issues and respond to the public issues every-time the private issues are done.

As a company maintaining public as well as private issues, how do keep them synced without logging the issues twice?? Also how do you maintain a Public Roadmap out of these issues??
